      {
        "id": 3251692,
        "name": "Adolfo H",
        "username": "Adolfo_H",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/adolfo_h/{size}/100835_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-10-10T17:31:15.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I used to work in cork, and I\u2019ve seen single piece sparkling done only once. I believe it was Mt. Eden winery making a tiny-volume sparkling cuvee for an anniversary celebration, and they needed roughly a thousand corks. Portugal chamfered large formats for the project.</p>\n<p>The cost was 10-15x the price of a grade A champagne cork. I do remember they were happy with the result.</p>\n<p>We did small runs for some beers for Bear Republic as well, but they used standard-sized wine corks.</p>\n<p>Edit: It was Kathryn Kennedy, not Mt. Eden. I knew it was SCM at least.</p>",
